# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: communication-complexity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In theoretical computer science, **communication complexity** studies the amount of communication required to solve a problem when the input to the problem is distributed among two or more parties.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The study of communication complexity was first introduced by Andrew Yao in 1979, while studying the problem of computation distributed among several machines.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The problem is usually stated as follows: two parties (traditionally called Alice and Bob) each receive a (potentially different) n -bit string x and y .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The goal is for Alice to compute the value of a certain function, $f(x,y)$ , that depends on both x and y , with the least amount of communication between them.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] While Alice and Bob can always succeed by having Bob send his whole n -bit string to Alice (who then computes the function f ), the idea here is to find clever ways of calculating *f* with fewer than n bits of communication.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Note that, unlike in computational complexity theory, communication complexity is not concerned with the amount of computation performed by Alice or Bob, or the size of the memory used, as we generally assume nothing about the computational power of either Alice or Bob.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This abstract problem with two parties (called two-party communication complexity), and its general form with more than two parties, is relevant in many contexts.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In VLSI circuit design, for example, one seeks to minimize energy used by decreasing the amount of electric signals passed between the different components during a distributed computation.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The problem is also relevant in the study of data structures and in the optimization of computer networks.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] For surveys of the field, see the textbooks by Rao & Yehudayoff (2020) and Kushilevitz & Nisan (2006).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Alice holds an n -bit string $x\in X$ while Bob holds an n -bit string $y\in Y$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] By communicating to each other one bit at a time (adopting some *communication protocol* that is agreed upon in advance), Alice and Bob wish to compute the value of $f(x,y)$ such that at least one party knows the value at the end of the communication.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] At this point the answer can be communicated back so that at the cost of one extra bit, both parties will know the answer.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] minimum number of bits exchanged between Alice and Bob in the worst case.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Using the above definition, it is useful to think of the function f as a matrix A (called the *input matrix* or *communication matrix*) where the rows are indexed by $x\in X$ and columns by $y\in Y$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The entries of the matrix are $A_{x,y}=f(x,y)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Initially both Alice and Bob have a copy of the entire matrix A (assuming the function f is known to both parties).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Then the problem of computing the function value can be rephrased as "zeroing-in" on the corresponding matrix entry.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This problem can be solved if either Alice or Bob knows both x and y .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] At the start of communication, the number of choices for the matrix position corresponding to the inputs is the size of matrix, i.e. $2^{2n}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Then, as and when each party communicates a bit to the other, the number of choices for the position reduces, as this eliminates a set of rows/columns, resulting in a submatrix of A .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Equivalently, R is a combinatorial rectangle if it can be expressed as $R=M\times N$ for some $M\subseteq X$ and $N\subseteq Y$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Consider the case when k bits are already exchanged between the parties.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Then $T_{h}\subseteq X\times Y$ , and it is not hard to show that $T_{h}$ is a combinatorial rectangle in A .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] We consider the case where Alice and Bob try to determine whether or not their input strings are equal.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] As we demonstrate below, any deterministic communication protocol solving $EQ$ requires n bits of communication in the worst case.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] As a warm-up example, consider the simple case of $x,y\in \{0,1\}^{3}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The equality function in this case can be represented by the matrix below.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The rows represent all the possibilities of x , the columns those of y .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In this table, the function only evaluates to 1 when x equals y (i.e., on the diagonal).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] It is also fairly easy to see how communicating a single bit divides someone's possibilities in half.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] When the first bit of y is 1, consider only half of the columns (where y can equal 100, 101, 110, or 111).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This means that there exists $x\neq x'$ such that $(x,x)$ and $(x',x')$ have the same communication transcript h .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since this transcript defines a rectangle, $f(x,x')$ must also be 1.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] By definition $x\neq x'$ and we know that equality is only true for $(a,b)$ when $a=b$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This technique of proving deterministic communication lower bounds is called the *fooling set* technique.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In the above definition, we are concerned with the number of bits that must be *deterministically* transmitted between two parties.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] If both the parties are given access to a random number generator, can they determine the value of f with much less information exchanged?
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Yao, in his seminal paper answers this question by defining **randomized communication complexity**.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A randomized protocol R for a function f has two-sided error.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A randomized protocol is a deterministic protocol that uses an extra random string in addition to its normal input.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] There are two models for this: a *public string* is a random string that is known by both parties beforehand, while a *private string* is generated by one party and must be communicated to the other party.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A theorem presented below shows that any public string protocol can be simulated by a private string protocol that uses *O(log n)* additional bits compared to the original.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In the probability inequalities above, the outcome of the protocol is understood to depend *only* on the random string; both strings *x* and *y* remain fixed.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The randomized complexity is simply defined as the number of bits exchanged in such a protocol.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Note that it is also possible to define a randomized protocol with one-sided error, and the complexity is defined similarly.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Returning to the previous example of *EQ*, if certainty is not required, Alice and Bob can check for equality using only ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠ messages.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Consider the following protocol: Assume that Alice and Bob both have access to the same random string $z\in \{0,1\}^{n}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Alice computes $z\cdot x$ and sends this bit (call it *b*) to Bob.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] (The $(\cdot )$ is the dot product in GF(2).) Then Bob compares *b* to $z\cdot y$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] If they are the same, then Bob accepts, saying *x* equals *y*.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] If *x* does not equal *y*, it is still possible that $z\cdot x=z\cdot y$ , which would give Bob the wrong answer.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Where x and y agree, $z_{i}*x_{i}=z_{i}*c_{i}=z_{i}*y_{i}$ so those terms affect the dot products equally.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] We can safely ignore those terms and look only at where x and y differ.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Furthermore, we can swap the bits $x_{i}$ and $y_{i}$ without changing whether or not the dot products are equal.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Now, the question becomes: for some random string $z'$ , what is the probability that $\Sigma _{i}z'_{i}=0$ ?
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since each $z'_{i}$ is equally likely to be 0 or 1, this probability is just $1/2$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Thus, when x does not equal y, $Prob_{z}[Accept]=1/2$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The algorithm can be repeated many times to increase its accuracy.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This fits the requirements for a randomized communication algorithm.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This shows that *if Alice and Bob share a random string of length n*, they can send one bit to each other to compute $EQ(x,y)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In the next section, it is shown that Alice and Bob can exchange only ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠ bits that are as good as sharing a random string of length *n*.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Once that is shown, it follows that *EQ* can be computed in ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠ messages.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] For yet another example of randomized communication complexity, we turn to an example known as the *gap-Hamming problem* (abbreviated *GH*).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Formally, Alice and Bob both maintain binary messages, $x,y\in \{-1,+1\}^{n}$ and would like to determine if the strings are very similar or if they are not very similar.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Clearly, they must communicate all their bits if the protocol is to be deterministic (this is because, if there is a deterministic, strict subset of indices that Alice and Bob relay to one another, then imagine having a pair of strings that on that set disagree in ${\sqrt {n}}-1$ positions.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] If another disagreement occurs in any position that is not relayed, then this affects the result of ${\text{GH}}_{n}(x,y)$ , and hence would result in an incorrect procedure.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A natural question one then asks is, if we're permitted to err $1/3$ of the time (over random instances $x,y$ drawn uniformly at random from $\{-1,+1\}^{n}$ ), then can we get away with a protocol with fewer bits?
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] It turns out that the answer somewhat surprisingly is no, due to a result of Chakrabarti and Regev in 2012: they show that for random instances, any procedure that is correct at least $2/3$ of the time must send $\Omega (n)$ bits worth of communication, which is to say essentially all of them.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Creating random protocols becomes easier when both parties have access to the same random string, known as a shared string protocol.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] However, even in cases where the two parties do not share a random string, it is still possible to use private string protocols with only a small communication cost.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Any shared string random protocol using any number of random string can be simulated by a private string protocol that uses an extra *O(log n)* bits.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Intuitively, we can find some set of strings that has enough randomness in it to run the random protocol with only a small increase in error.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This set can be shared beforehand, and instead of drawing a random string, Alice and Bob need only agree on which string to choose from the shared set.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This set is small enough that the choice can be communicated efficiently.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Consider some random protocol *P* with a maximum error rate of 0.1.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Given such an R , define a new protocol $P'_{R}$ that randomly picks some $r_{i}$ and then runs *P* using $r_{i}$ as the shared random string.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] It takes *O*(log 100*n*) = *O*(log *n*) bits to communicate the choice of $r_{i}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Let us define $p(x,y)$ and $p'_{R}(x,y)$ to be the probabilities that P and $P'_{R}$ compute the correct value for the input $(x,y)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The last equality above holds because there are $2^{2n}$ different pairs $(x,y)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since P has at most 0.1 error probability, $P'_{R_{0}}$ can have at most 0.2 error probability.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Let's say we additionally allow Alice and Bob to share some resource, for example a pair of entangled particles.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Using that ressource, Alice and Bob can correlate their information and thus try to 'collapse' (or 'trivialize') communication complexity in the following sense.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The surprising fact of a collapse of communication complexity is that the function f can have arbitrarily large entry size, but still the number of communication bit is constant to a single one.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Some resources are shown to be non-collapsing, such as quantum correlations or more generally almost-quantum correlations, whereas on the contrary some other resources are shown to collapse randomized communication complexity, such as the PR-box, or some noisy PR-boxes satisfying some conditions.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] One approach to studying randomized communication complexity is through distributional complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Given a joint distribution $\mu$ on the inputs of both players, the corresponding distributional complexity of a function f is the minimum cost of a *deterministic* protocol R such that $\Pr[f(x,y)=R(x,y)]\geq 2/3$ , where the inputs are sampled according to $\mu$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Yao's minimax principle (a special case of von Neumann's minimax theorem) states that the randomized communication complexity of a function equals its maximum distributional complexity, where the maximum is taken over all joint distributions of the inputs (not necessarily product distributions!).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Yao's principle can be used to prove lower bounds on the randomized communication complexity of a function: design the appropriate joint distribution, and prove a lower bound on the distributional complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since distributional complexity concerns deterministic protocols, this could be easier than proving a lower bound on randomized protocols directly.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] As an example, let us consider the *disjointness* function DISJ: each of the inputs is interpreted as a subset of $\{1,\dots ,n\}$ , and DISJ(x,y)=1 if the two sets are disjoint.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Razborov proved an $\Omega (n)$ lower bound on the randomized communication complexity by considering the following distribution: with probability 3/4, sample two random disjoint sets of size $n/4$ , and with probability 1/4, sample two random sets of size $n/4$ with a unique intersection.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A powerful approach to the study of distributional complexity is information complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Initiated by Bar-Yossef, Jayram, Kumar and Sivakumar, the approach was codified in work of Barak, Braverman, Chen and Rao and by Braverman and Rao.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The (internal) information complexity of a (possibly randomized) protocol R with respect to a distribution μ is defined as follows.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Let $(X,Y)\sim \mu$ be random inputs sampled according to μ, and let Π be the transcript of R when run on the inputs $X,Y$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] where I denotes conditional mutual information.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The first summand measures the amount of information that Alice learns about Bob's input from the transcript, and the second measures the amount of information that Bob learns about Alice's input.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The ε-error information complexity of a function f with respect to a distribution μ is the infimal information complexity of a protocol for f whose error (with respect to μ) is at most ε.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Braverman and Rao proved that information equals amortized communication.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This means that the cost for solving n independent copies of f is roughly n times the information complexity of f.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This is analogous to the well-known interpretation of Shannon entropy as the amortized bit-length required to transmit data from a given information source.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Braverman and Rao's proof uses a technique known as "protocol compression", in which an information-efficient protocol is "compressed" into a communication-efficient protocol.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The techniques of information complexity enable the computation of the exact (up to first order) communication complexity of set disjointness to be $1.4923\ldots n$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Information complexity techniques have also been used to analyze extended formulations, proving an essentially optimal lower bound on the complexity of algorithms based on linear programming that approximately solve the maximum clique problem.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Omri Weinstein's 2015 survey surveys the subject.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Quantum communication complexity tries to quantify the communication reduction possible by using quantum effects during a distributed computation.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] At least three quantum generalizations of communication complexity have been proposed; for a survey see the suggested text by G.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The first one is the qubit-communication model, where the parties can use quantum communication instead of classical communication, for example by exchanging photons through an optical fiber.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In a second model the communication is still performed with classical bits, but the parties are allowed to manipulate an unlimited supply of quantum entangled states as part of their protocols.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] By doing measurements on their entangled states, the parties can save on classical communication during a distributed computation (see an application in Collapse of Randomized Communication Complexity).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The third model involves access to previously shared entanglement in addition to qubit communication, and is the least explored of the three quantum models.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In nondeterministic communication complexity, Alice and Bob have access to an oracle.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] After receiving the oracle's word, the parties communicate to deduce $f(x,y)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The nondeterministic communication complexity is then the maximum over all pairs $(x,y)$ over the sum of number of bits exchanged and the coding length of the oracle word.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Viewed differently, this amounts to covering all 1-entries of the 0/1-matrix by combinatorial 1-rectangles (i.e., non-contiguous, non-convex submatrices, whose entries are all one (see Kushilevitz and Nisan or Dietzfelbinger et al.)).
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The nondeterministic communication complexity is the binary logarithm of the *rectangle covering number* of the matrix: the minimum number of combinatorial 1-rectangles required to cover all 1-entries of the matrix, without covering any 0-entries.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Nondeterministic communication complexity occurs as a means to obtaining lower bounds for deterministic communication complexity (see Dietzfelbinger et al.), but also in the theory of nonnegative matrices, where it gives a lower bound on the nonnegative rank of a nonnegative matrix.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In the unbounded-error setting, Alice and Bob have access to a private coin and their own inputs $(x,y)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In this setting, Alice succeeds if she responds with the correct value of $f(x,y)$ with probability strictly greater than 1/2.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In other words, if Alice's responses have *any* non-zero correlation to the true value of $f(x,y)$ , then the protocol is considered valid.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Note that the requirement that the coin is *private* is essential.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In particular, if the number of public bits shared between Alice and Bob are not counted against the communication complexity, it is easy to argue that computing any function has $O(1)$ communication complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] On the other hand, both models are equivalent if the number of public bits used by Alice and Bob is counted against the protocol's total communication.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Though subtle, lower bounds on this model are extremely strong.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] More specifically, it is clear that any bound on problems of this class immediately imply equivalent bounds on problems in the deterministic model and the private and public coin models, but such bounds also hold immediately for nondeterministic communication models and quantum communication models.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Lifting is a general technique in complexity theory in which a lower bound on a simple measure of complexity is "lifted" to a lower bound on a more difficult measure.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This technique was pioneered in the context of communication complexity by Raz and McKenzie, who proved the first query-to-communication lifting theorem, and used the result to separate the monotone NC hierarchy.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In words, x is partitioned into n blocks of length a , and y is partitioned into n blocks of length b .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The gadget is applied n times on the blocks, and the outputs are fed into f .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In this diagram, each of the inputs $\mathbf {x} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {x} _{n}$ is a bits long, and each of the inputs $\mathbf {y} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {y} _{n}$ is b bits long.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A decision tree of depth $\Delta$ for f can be translated to a communication protocol whose cost is $\Delta \cdot D(g)$ : each time the tree queries a bit, the corresponding value of g is computed using an optimal protocol for g .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Raz and McKenzie showed that this is optimal up to a constant factor when g is the so-called "indexing gadget", in which x has length $c\log n$ (for a large enough constant c), y has length $n^{c}$ , and $g(x,y)$ is the x -th bit of y .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The proof of the Raz–McKenzie lifting theorem uses the method of simulation, in which a protocol for the composed function $f\circ g$ is used to generate a decision tree for f .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Göös, Pitassi and Watson gave an exposition of the original proof.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since then, several works have proved similar theorems with different gadgets, such as inner product.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The smallest gadget that can be handled is the indexing gadget with $c=1+\epsilon$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Göös, Pitassi and Watson extended the Raz–McKenzie technique to randomized protocols.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A simple modification of the Raz–McKenzie lifting theorem gives a lower bound of $\Delta \cdot D(g)$ on the logarithm of the size of a protocol tree for computing $f\circ g$ , where $\Delta$ is the depth of the optimal decision tree for f .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Garg, Göös, Kamath and Sokolov extended this to the DAG-like setting, and used their result to obtain monotone circuit lower bounds.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The same technique has also yielded applications to proof complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] A different type of lifting is exemplified by Sherstov's pattern matrix method, which gives a lower bound on the quantum communication complexity of $f\circ g$ , where g is a modified indexing gadget, in terms of the approximate degree of f.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The approximate degree of a Boolean function is the minimal degree of a polynomial that approximates the function on all Boolean points up to an additive error of 1/3.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] In contrast to the Raz–McKenzie proof, which uses the method of simulation, Sherstov's proof takes a *dual witness* to the approximate degree of f and gives a lower bound on the quantum query complexity of $f\circ g$ using the *generalized discrepancy method*.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The dual witness for the approximate degree of f is a lower bound witness for the approximate degree obtained via LP duality.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This dual witness is massaged into other objects constituting data for the generalized discrepancy method.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Another example of this approach is the work of Pitassi and Robere, in which an *algebraic gap* is lifted to a lower bound on Razborov's *rank measure*.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The result is a strongly exponential lower bound on the monotone circuit complexity of an explicit function, obtained via the Karchmer–Wigderson characterization of monotone circuit size in terms of communication complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Considering a 0 or 1 input matrix $M_{f}=[f(x,y)]_{x,y\in \{0,1\}^{n}}$ , the minimum number of bits exchanged to compute f deterministically in the worst case, $D(f)$ , is known to be bounded from below by the logarithm of the rank of the matrix $M_{f}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] The log rank conjecture proposes that the communication complexity, $D(f)$ , is bounded from above by a constant power of the logarithm of the rank of $M_{f}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since D(f) is bounded from above and below by polynomials of log rank $(M_{f})$ , we can say D(f) is polynomially related to log rank $(M_{f})$ .
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Since the rank of a matrix is polynomial time computable in the size of the matrix, such an upper bound would allow the matrix's communication complexity to be approximated in polynomial time.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Note, however, that the size of the matrix itself is exponential in the size of the input.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Such log rank conjectures are valuable because they reduce the question of a matrix's communication complexity to a question of linearly independent rows (columns) of the matrix.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This particular version, called the Log-Approximate-Rank Conjecture, was recently refuted by Chattopadhyay, Mande and Sherif (2019) using a surprisingly simple counter-example.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] This reveals that the essence of the communication complexity problem, for example in the EQ case above, is figuring out where in the matrix the inputs are, in order to find out if they're equivalent.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Lower bounds in communication complexity can be used to prove lower bounds in decision tree complexity, VLSI circuits, data structures, streaming algorithms, space–time tradeoffs for Turing machines and more.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Conitzer and Sandholm studied the communication complexity of some common voting rules, which are essential in political and non political organizations.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Compilation complexity is a closely related notion, which can be seen as a single-round communication complexity.
[src:communication-complexity/communication-complexity] Nayebi has studied the communication complexity of unbounded and bounded Bayesians, establishing no-free-lunch theorems (lower bounds) on AI alignment.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] In the classical setting, we aim at partitioning the vertices of a hypergraph ${\mathcal {H}}=(V,{\mathcal {E}})$ into two classes in such a way that ideally each hyperedge contains the same number of vertices in both classes.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] A partition into two classes can be represented by a coloring $\chi \colon V\rightarrow \{-1,+1\}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] These notions as well as the term 'discrepancy' seem to have appeared for the first time in a paper of Beck.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Earlier results on this problem include the famous lower bound on the discrepancy of arithmetic progressions by Roth and upper bounds for this problem and other results by Erdős and Spencer and Sárközi.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] At that time, discrepancy problems were called *quasi-Ramsey problems*.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] To get some intuition for this concept, let's have a look at a few examples.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] The last example shows that we cannot expect to determine the discrepancy by looking at a single parameter like the number of hyperedges.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Still, the size of the hypergraph yields first upper bounds.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] The proof is a simple application of the probabilistic method.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Since $\chi (E)=\sum _{v\in E}\chi (v)$ is a sum of independent −1, 1 random variables.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Since a random coloring with positive probability has discrepancy at most $\lambda$ , in particular, there are colorings that have discrepancy at most $\lambda$ .
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] To prove this, a much more sophisticated approach using the entropy function was necessary.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Of course this is particularly interesting for $m=O(n)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] In the case $m=n$ , $\operatorname {disc} ({\mathcal {H}})\leq 6{\sqrt {n}}$ can be shown for n large enough.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Therefore, this result is usually known to as 'Six Standard Deviations Suffice'.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] It is considered to be one of the milestones of discrepancy theory.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] The entropy method has seen numerous other applications, e.g. in the proof of the tight upper bound for the arithmetic progressions of Matoušek and Spencer or the upper bound in terms of the primal shatter function due to Matoušek.
[src:communication-complexity/discrepancy-of-hypergraphs] Better discrepancy bounds can be attained when the hypergraph has a *bounded degree*, that is, each vertex of ${\mathcal {H}}$ is contained in at most *t* edges, for some small *t*.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory was initially formed in the context of telecommunication but soon found a wide range of other applications.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] It is now at the intersection of mathematics, statistics and computer science, and has applications in diverse fields ranging from electrical engineering and physics to neurobiology.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] As a simple example of the concept, if one flips a fair coin and does not yet know the outcome (heads or tails), then they lack a certain amount of information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] After looking at the coin, they gain information about the outcome.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For a fair coin, the probability of either heads or tails is 1/2 and the amount of information is expressed as $-\log _{2}(1/2)$ = 1 bit of information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A key concept in information theory is entropy.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In Shannon's formulation entropy is equal to the lack of information about an event.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In the above coin flip example, the entropy in the case where you don't know the outcome is 1 bit.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] When you know the outcome after the coin has landed, the entropy is zero because you have gained one bit.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory has been used in a wide range of applications, such as source coding/data compression (e.g. for ZIP files), and channel coding/error detection and correction (e.g. for DSL).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Its impact has been crucial to the success of the Voyager missions to deep space, the invention of the compact disc, the feasibility of mobile phones and the development of the Internet and artificial intelligence.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory, as conceived by Claude Shannon, studies the processing and utilization of information within a probabilistic context.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Abstractly, in this approach information can be thought of as the resolution of uncertainty.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Shannon's main result, the noisy-channel coding theorem, showed that, in the limit of many channel uses, the rate of information that is asymptotically achievable is equal to the channel capacity, a quantity dependent merely on the statistics of the channel over which the messages are sent.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Coding theory is concerned with finding explicit methods, called *codes*, for increasing the efficiency and reducing the error rate of data communication over noisy channels to near the channel capacity.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] These codes can be roughly subdivided into data compression (source coding) and error-correction (channel coding) techniques.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In the latter case, it took many years to find the methods Shannon's work proved were possible.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A third class of information theory codes are cryptographic algorithms (both codes and ciphers).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Concepts, methods and results from coding theory and information theory are widely used in cryptography and cryptanalysis, such as the unit ban.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The landmark event *establishing* the discipline of information theory and bringing it to immediate worldwide attention was the publication of Claude Shannon's classic paper "A Mathematical Theory of Communication" in the *Bell System Technical Journal* in July and October 1948.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Historian James Gleick rated the paper as the most important development of 1948, noting that the paper was "even more profound and more fundamental" than the transistor.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] He came to be known as the "father of information theory".
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Shannon outlined some of his initial ideas of information theory as early as 1939 in a letter to Vannevar Bush.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Prior to this paper, limited information-theoretic ideas had been developed at Bell Labs, all implicitly assuming events of equal probability.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The unit of information was therefore the decimal digit, which since has sometimes been called the hartley in his honor as a unit or scale or measure of information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Alan Turing in 1940 used similar ideas as part of the statistical analysis of the breaking of the German second world war Enigma ciphers.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Much of the mathematics behind information theory with events of different probabilities were developed for the field of thermodynamics by Ludwig Boltzmann and J.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Connections between information-theoretic entropy and thermodynamic entropy, including the important contributions by Rolf Landauer in the 1960s, are explored in *Entropy in thermodynamics and information theory*.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The fundamental problem of communication is that of reproducing at one point, either exactly or approximately, a message selected at another point.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory is based on probability theory and statistics, where quantified information is usually described in terms of bits.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory often concerns itself with measures of information of the distributions associated with random variables.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] One of the most important measures is called entropy, which forms the building block of many other measures.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Entropy allows quantification of measure of information in a single random variable.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Another useful concept is mutual information defined on two random variables, which quantifies the dependence between those variables, which is done by comparing the conditional and unconditional distributions.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The former quantity is a property of the probability distribution of a random variable and gives a limit on the rate at which data generated by independent samples with the given distribution can be reliably compressed.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The latter is a property of the joint distribution of two random variables and is the maximum rate of reliable communication across a noisy channel in the limit of long block lengths, when the channel statistics are determined by the joint distribution.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The choice of logarithmic base in the following formulae determines the unit of information entropy that is used.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A common unit of information is the bit or shannon, based on the binary logarithm.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Other units include the nat, which is based on the natural logarithm, and the decimal digit, which is based on the common logarithm.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In what follows, an expression of the form *p* log *p* is considered by convention to be equal to zero whenever *p* = 0.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This is justified because $\lim _{p\rightarrow 0^{+}}p\log p=0$ for any logarithmic base.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Based on the probability mass function of a source, the Shannon entropy *H*, in units of bits per symbol, is defined as the expected value of the information content of the symbols.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The amount of information conveyed by an individual source symbol $x_{i}$ with probability $p_{i}$ is known as its **self-information** or **surprisal**, $I(p_{i})$ .
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A less probable symbol has a larger surprisal, meaning its occurrence provides more information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Intuitively, the entropy $H(X)$ of a discrete random variable *X* is a measure of the amount of *uncertainty* associated with the value of X when only its distribution is known.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A high entropy indicates the outcomes are more evenly distributed, making the result harder to predict.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For example, if one transmits 1000 bits (0s and 1s), and the value of each of these bits is known to the receiver (has a specific value with certainty) ahead of transmission, no information is transmitted.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] If, however, each bit is independently and equally likely to be 0 or 1, 1000 shannons of information (more often called bits) have been transmitted.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A key property of entropy is that it is maximized when all the messages in the message space are equiprobable.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This maximum value represents the most unpredictable state.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For a source that emits a sequence of N symbols that are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.), the total entropy of the message is $N\cdot H$ bits.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] If the source data symbols are identically distributed but not independent, the entropy of a message of length N will be less than $N\cdot H$ .
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The special case of information entropy for a random variable with two outcomes (a Bernoulli trial) is the **binary entropy function**.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This is typically calculated using a base-2 logarithm, and its unit is the shannon.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] If one outcome has probability p, the other has probability *1* − *p*.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This function is depicted in the plot shown above, reaching its maximum of 1 bit when *p* = 0.5, corresponding to the highest uncertainty.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The *joint entropy* of two discrete random variables *X* and *Y* is merely the entropy of their pairing: (*X*, *Y*).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This implies that if *X* and *Y* are independent, then their joint entropy is the sum of their individual entropies.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For example, if (*X*, *Y*) represents the position of a chess piece—*X* the row and *Y* the column, then the joint entropy of the row of the piece and the column of the piece will be the entropy of the position of the piece.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Despite similar notation, joint entropy should not be confused with *cross-entropy*.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Thus, joint entropy is just a subcase of entropy where the random variable is a vector giving values in the product space.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Because entropy can be conditioned on a random variable or on that random variable being a certain value, care should be taken not to confuse these two definitions of conditional entropy, the former of which is in more common use.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] where SI (*S*pecific mutual Information) is the pointwise mutual information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] That is, knowing ${\textstyle Y}$ , we can save an average of *I*(*X*; *Y*) bits in encoding *X* compared to not knowing Y .
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In other words, this is a measure of how much, on the average, the probability distribution on X will change if we are given the value of *${\textstyle Y}$*.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The *Kullback–Leibler divergence* (or *information divergence*, *information gain*, or *relative entropy*) is a way of comparing two distributions: a "true" probability distribution ⁠ $p(X)$ ⁠, and an arbitrary probability distribution ⁠ $q(X)$ ⁠.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] If we compress data in a manner that assumes ⁠ $q(X)$ ⁠ is the distribution underlying some data, when, in reality, ⁠ $p(X)$ ⁠ is the correct distribution, the Kullback–Leibler divergence is the number of average additional bits per datum necessary for compression.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Although it is sometimes used as a 'distance metric', KL divergence is not a true metric since it is not symmetric and does not satisfy the triangle inequality (making it a semi-quasimetric).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Another interpretation of the KL divergence is the "unnecessary surprise" introduced by a prior from the truth: suppose a number *X* is about to be drawn randomly from a discrete set with probability distribution ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] If Alice knows the true distribution ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠, while Bob believes (has a prior) that the distribution is ⁠ $q(x)$ ⁠, then Bob will be more surprised than Alice, on average, upon seeing the value of X .
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The KL divergence is the (objective) expected value of Bob's (subjective) surprisal minus Alice's surprisal, measured in bits if the *log* is in base 2.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In this way, the extent to which Bob's prior is "wrong" can be quantified in terms of how "unnecessarily surprised" it is expected to make him.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The Kullback Leibler information provides a link between information theory and hypothesis testing, as it is the optimal error exponent in asymmetric hypothesis testing.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In contrast to *mutual* information, *directed* information is not symmetric.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The $I(X^{n}\to Y^{n})$ measures the information bits that are transmitted causally from $X^{n}$ to $Y^{n}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Other important information theoretic quantities include the Rényi entropy and the Tsallis entropy (generalizations of the concept of entropy), differential entropy (a generalization of quantities of information to continuous distributions), and the conditional mutual information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Also, pragmatic information has been proposed as a measure of how much information has been used in making a decision.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Coding theory is one of the most important and direct applications of information theory.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] It can be subdivided into source coding theory and channel coding theory.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Using a statistical description for data, information theory quantifies the number of bits needed to describe the data, which is the information entropy of the source.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This division of coding theory into compression and transmission is justified by the information transmission theorems, or source–channel separation theorems that justify the use of bits as the universal currency for information in many contexts.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] However, these theorems only hold in the situation where one transmitting user wishes to communicate to one receiving user.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In scenarios with more than one transmitter (the multiple-access channel), more than one receiver (the broadcast channel) or intermediary "helpers" (the relay channel), or more general networks, compression followed by transmission may no longer be optimal.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For general sources and channels that are not necessarily stationary or ergodic, information-spectrum methods characterize coding limits using asymptotic distributions of information density rather than only single-letter entropies or mutual information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A related problem, channel resolvability, asks what rate is required for channel inputs to approximate a target output distribution; Han and Sergio Verdú connected this approximation problem to coding theorems for general channels.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Any process that generates successive messages can be considered a *source* of information.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A memoryless source is one in which each message is an independent identically distributed random variable, whereas the properties of ergodicity and stationarity impose less restrictive constraints.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] These terms are well studied in their own right outside information theory.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information *rate* is the average entropy per symbol.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] that is, the conditional entropy of a symbol given all the previous symbols generated.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] that is, the limit of the joint entropy per symbol.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For stationary sources, these two expressions give the same result.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] It is common in information theory to speak of the "rate" or "entropy" of a language.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This is appropriate, for example, when the source of information is English prose.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The rate of a source of information is related to its redundancy and how well it can be compressed, the subject of *source coding*.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Communications over a channel is the primary motivation of information theory.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] However, channels often fail to produce exact reconstruction of a signal; noise, periods of silence, and other forms of signal corruption often degrade quality.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Consider the communications process over a discrete channel.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Here X represents the space of messages transmitted, and ${\textstyle Y}$ the space of messages received during a unit time over our channel.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Let *p*(*y*|*x*) be the conditional probability distribution function of *${\textstyle Y}$* given X .
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] We will consider *p*(*y*|*x*) to be an inherent fixed property of our communications channel (representing the nature of the *noise* of our channel).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Then the joint distribution of *X* and *${\textstyle Y}$* is completely determined by our channel and by our choice of *f*(*x*), the marginal distribution of messages we choose to send over the channel.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Under these constraints, we would like to maximize the rate of information, or the *signal*, we can communicate over the channel.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] This capacity has the following property related to communicating at information rate *R* (where *R* is usually bits per symbol).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] For any information rate *R* < *C* and coding error *ε* > 0, for large enough *N*, there exists a code of length *N* and rate ≥ R and a decoding algorithm, such that the maximal probability of block error is ≤ *ε*; that is, it is always possible to transmit with arbitrarily small block error.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In addition, for any rate *R* > *C*, it is impossible to transmit with arbitrarily small block error.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In such a case the capacity is given by the mutual information rate when there is no feedback available and the Directed information rate in the case that either there is feedback or not (if there is no feedback the directed information equals the mutual information).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theoretic concepts apply to cryptography and cryptanalysis.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Turing's information unit, the ban, was used in the Ultra project, breaking the German Enigma machine code and hastening the end of World War II in Europe.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Shannon himself defined an important concept now called the unicity distance.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Based on the redundancy of the plaintext, it attempts to give a minimum amount of ciphertext necessary to ensure unique decipherability.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory leads us to believe it is much more difficult to keep secrets than it might first appear.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A brute force attack can break systems based on asymmetric key algorithms or on most commonly used methods of symmetric key algorithms (sometimes called secret key algorithms), such as block ciphers.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The security of all such methods comes from the assumption that no known attack can break them in a practical amount of time.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theoretic security refers to methods such as the one-time pad that are not vulnerable to such brute force attacks.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In such cases, the positive conditional mutual information between the plaintext and ciphertext (conditioned on the key) can ensure proper transmission, while the unconditional mutual information between the plaintext and ciphertext remains zero, resulting in absolutely secure communications.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] In other words, an eavesdropper would not be able to improve his or her guess of the plaintext by gaining knowledge of the ciphertext but not of the key.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] However, as in any other cryptographic system, care must be used to correctly apply even information-theoretically secure methods; the Venona project was able to crack the one-time pads of the Soviet Union due to their improper reuse of key material.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Pseudorandom number generators are widely available in computer language libraries and application programs.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] They are, almost universally, unsuited to cryptographic use as they do not evade the deterministic nature of modern computer equipment and software.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] A class of improved random number generators is termed cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators, but even they require random seeds external to the software to work as intended.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] These can be obtained via extractors, if done carefully.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] The measure of sufficient randomness in extractors is min-entropy, a value related to Shannon entropy through Rényi entropy; Rényi entropy is also used in evaluating randomness in cryptographic systems.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Although related, the distinctions among these measures mean that a random variable with high Shannon entropy is not necessarily satisfactory for use in an extractor and so for cryptography uses.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] One early commercial application of information theory was in the field of seismic oil exploration.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Work in this field made it possible to strip off and separate the unwanted noise from the desired seismic signal.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory and digital signal processing offer a major improvement of resolution and image clarity over previous analog methods.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Semioticians Doede Nauta and Winfried Nöth both considered Charles Sanders Peirce as having created a theory of information in his works on semiotics.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Quantitative information theoretic methods have been applied in cognitive science to analyze the integrated process organization of neural information in the context of the binding problem in cognitive neuroscience.
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Friston's free energy principle (FEP), an information-theoretical measure which states that every adaptive change in a self-organized system leads to a minimization of free energy, and the Bayesian brain hypothesis).
[src:communication-complexity/information-theory] Information theory also has applications in the search for extraterrestrial intelligence, black holes, bioinformatics, and gambling.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Recall that the contraction of two nodes, *u* and *v*, in a (multi-)graph yields a new node *u* ' with edges that are the union of the edges incident on either *u* or *v*, except from any edge(s) connecting *u* and *v*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Figure 1 gives an example of contraction of vertex *A* and *B*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] After contraction, the resulting graph may have parallel edges, but contains no self loops.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] In each execution of the outer loop, the algorithm repeats the inner loop until only 2 nodes remain, the corresponding cut is obtained.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The run time of one execution is $O(n)$ , and *n* denotes the number of vertices.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] After *m* times executions of the outer loop, we output the minimum cut among all the results.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The figure 2 gives an example of one execution of the algorithm.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] After execution, we get a cut of size 3.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] If *G* is not connected, then *G* can be partitioned into *L* and *R* without any edge between them.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] So the min cut in a disconnected graph is 0.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Initially, *u*,*v* are distinct vertices.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] *As long as we pick an edge ⁠ $f\neq e$ ⁠, u and v do not get merged.* Thus, at the end of the algorithm, we have two compound nodes covering the entire graph, one consisting of the vertices of *L* and the other consisting of the vertices of *R*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] As in figure 2, the size of min cut is 1, and *C* = {(*A*,*B*)}.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] If we don't select (*A*,*B*) for contraction, we can get the min cut.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Because the min cut is *k*, every vertex *v* must satisfy degree(*v*) ≥ *k*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, the sum of the degree is at least *pk*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] But it is well known that the sum of vertex degrees equals 2|*E*|.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the algorithm succeeds is 1 − the probability that all attempts fail.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] By lemma 1, the probability that *C**i* = *C* is the probability that no edge of *C* is selected during iteration *i*.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Consider the inner loop and let *G**j* denote the graph after *j* edge contractions, where *j* ∈ {0, 1, …, *n* − 3}.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] We use the chain rule of conditional possibilities.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the edge chosen at iteration *j* is not in *C*, given that no edge of *C* has been chosen before, is $1-{\frac {k}{|E(G_{j})|}}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Note that *G**j* still has min cut of size *k*, so by Lemma 2, it still has at least ${\frac {(n-j)k}{2}}$ edges.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Thus the probability that the algorithm succeeds is at least $1-\left(1-{\frac {2}{n(n-1)}}\right)^{m}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] The algorithm finds the min cut with probability $1-{\frac {1}{n}}$ , in time $O(mn)=O(n^{3}\log n)$ .
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:communication-complexity/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] In mathematics, a **Riemann sum** is a certain kind of approximation of an integral by a finite sum.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] It is named after nineteenth century German mathematician Bernhard Riemann.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] One very common application is in numerical integration, i.e., approximating the area of functions or lines on a graph, where it is also known as the **rectangle rule**.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] It can also be applied for approximating the length of curves and other approximations.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This approach can be used to find a numerical approximation for a definite integral even if the fundamental theorem of calculus does not make it easy to find a closed-form solution.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Because the region by the small shapes is usually not exactly the same shape as the region being measured, the Riemann sum will differ from the area being measured.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This error can be reduced by dividing up the region more finely, using smaller and smaller shapes.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] As the shapes get smaller and smaller, the sum approaches the Riemann integral.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] One might produce different Riemann sums depending on which $x_{i}^{*}$ s are chosen.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] In the end this will not matter, if the function is Riemann integrable, when the difference or width of the summands $\Delta x_{i}$ approaches zero.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] All these Riemann summation methods are among the most basic ways to accomplish numerical integration.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Loosely speaking, a function is Riemann integrable if all Riemann sums converge as the partition "gets finer and finer".
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] While not derived as a Riemann sum, taking the average of the left and right Riemann sums is the **trapezoidal rule** and gives a **trapezoidal sum**.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] It is one of the simplest of a very general way of approximating integrals using weighted averages.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This is followed in complexity by Simpson's rule and Newton–Cotes formulas.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Any Riemann sum on a given partition (that is, for any choice of $x_{i}^{*}$ between $x_{i-1}$ and $x_{i}$ ) is contained between the lower and upper Darboux sums.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This forms the basis of the Darboux integral, which is ultimately equivalent to the Riemann integral.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The four Riemann summation methods are usually best approached with subintervals of equal size.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For the left rule, the function is approximated by its values at the left endpoints of the subintervals.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This gives multiple rectangles with base Δ*x* and height *f*(*a* + *i*Δ*x*).
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The left Riemann sum amounts to an overestimation if *f* is monotonically decreasing on this interval, and an underestimation if it is monotonically increasing.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The error of this formula will be $\left\vert \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx-S_{\mathrm {left} }\right\vert \leq {\frac {M_{1}(b-a)^{2}}{2n}},$ where $M_{1}$ is the maximum value of the absolute value of $f^{\prime }(x)$ over the interval.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For the right rule, the function is approximated by its values at the right endpoints of the subintervals.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The right Riemann sum amounts to an underestimation if *f* is monotonically decreasing, and an overestimation if it is monotonically increasing.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The error of this formula will be $\left\vert \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx-S_{\mathrm {right} }\right\vert \leq {\frac {M_{1}(b-a)^{2}}{2n}},$ where $M_{1}$ is the maximum value of the absolute value of $f^{\prime }(x)$ over the interval.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For the midpoint rule, the function is approximated by its values at the midpoints of the subintervals.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The error of this formula will be $\left\vert \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx-S_{\mathrm {mid} }\right\vert \leq {\frac {M_{2}(b-a)^{3}}{24n^{2}}},$ where $M_{2}$ is the maximum value of the absolute value of $f^{\prime \prime }(x)$ over the interval.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This error is half of that of the trapezoidal sum; as such the middle Riemann sum is the most accurate approach to the Riemann sum.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For the trapezoidal rule, the function is approximated by the average of its values at the left and right endpoints of the subintervals.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The approximation obtained with the trapezoidal sum for a function is the same as the average of the left hand and right hand sums of that function.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For a one-dimensional Riemann sum over domain $[a,b]$ , as the maximum size of a subinterval shrinks to zero (that is the limit of the norm of the subintervals goes to zero), some functions will have all Riemann sums converge to the same value.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For a finite-sized domain, if the maximum size of a subinterval shrinks to zero, this implies the number of subinterval goes to infinity.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] For finite partitions, Riemann sums are always approximations to the limiting value and this approximation gets better as the partition gets finer.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Since the red function here is assumed to be a smooth function, all three Riemann sums will converge to the same value as the number of subintervals goes to infinity.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] over [0, 2] using the right Riemann sum.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Notice that because the function is monotonically increasing, the right Riemann sum will always overestimate the area contributed by each term in the sum (and do so maximally).
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Taking an example, the area under the curve *y* = *x*2 over [0, 2] can be procedurally computed using Riemann's method.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The interval [0, 2] is firstly divided into n subintervals, each of which is given a width of ${\tfrac {2}{n}}$ ; these are the widths of the Riemann rectangles (hereafter "boxes").
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Because the right Riemann sum is to be used, the sequence of x coordinates for the boxes will be $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] If the limit is viewed as *n* → ∞, it can be concluded that the approximation approaches the actual value of the area under the curve as the number of boxes increases.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Because the function is continuous and monotonically increasing over the interval, a right Riemann sum overestimates the integral by the largest amount (while a left Riemann sum would underestimate the integral by the largest amount).
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This fact, which is intuitively clear from the diagrams, shows how the nature of the function determines how accurate the integral is estimated.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] While simple, right and left Riemann sums are often less accurate than more advanced techniques of estimating an integral such as the Trapezoidal rule or Simpson's rule.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The example function has an easy-to-find anti-derivative so estimating the integral by Riemann sums is mostly an academic exercise; however it must be remembered that not all functions have anti-derivatives so estimating their integrals by summation is practically important.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] The basic idea behind a Riemann sum is to "break-up" the domain via a partition into pieces, multiply the "size" of each piece by some value the function takes on that piece, and sum all these products.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] This can be generalized to allow Riemann sums for functions over domains of more than one dimension.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] While intuitively, the process of partitioning the domain is easy to grasp, the technical details of how the domain may be partitioned get much more complicated than the one dimensional case and involves aspects of the geometrical shape of the domain.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] In two dimensions, the domain A may be divided into a number of two-dimensional cells $A_{i}$ such that ${\textstyle A=\bigcup _{i}A_{i}}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Each cell then can be interpreted as having an "area" denoted by $\Delta A_{i}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] In three dimensions, the domain V is partitioned into a number of three-dimensional cells $V_{i}$ such that ${\textstyle V=\bigcup _{i}V_{i}}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Each cell then can be interpreted as having a "volume" denoted by $\Delta V_{i}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Higher dimensional Riemann sums follow a similar pattern.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] In high generality, Riemann sums can be written $S=\sum _{i}f(P_{i}^{*})\mu (V_{i}),$ where $P_{i}^{*}$ stands for any arbitrary point contained in the set $V_{i}$ and $\mu$ is a measure on the underlying set.
[src:communication-complexity/rectangle-method] Roughly speaking, a measure is a function that gives a "size" of a set, in this case the size of the set $V_{i}$ ; in one dimension this can often be interpreted as a length, in two dimensions as an area, in three dimensions as a volume, and so on.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In computational complexity theory, **Yao's principle** (also called **Yao's minimax principle** or **Yao's lemma**) relates the performance of randomized algorithms to deterministic (non-random) algorithms.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle is often used to prove limitations on the performance of randomized algorithms, by finding a probability distribution on inputs that is difficult for deterministic algorithms, and inferring that randomized algorithms have the same limitation on their worst case performance.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] This principle is named after Andrew Yao, who first proposed it in a 1977 paper.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] It is closely related to the minimax theorem in the theory of zero-sum games, and to the duality theory of linear programs.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle is formulated in terms of an arbitrary real valued cost measure $c(A,x)$ of an algorithm A on an input x , such as its running time, for which one wishes to study the expected value over randomized algorithms and random inputs.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The algorithms used in this cost measure are drawn from a finite set ${\mathcal {A}}$ of deterministic algorithms; a typical way to make a problem have only a finite set of algorithms is to restrict its inputs to a single size.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The inputs, too, should be drawn from a finite set ${\mathcal {X}}$ , which can be made finite in the same way.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Finally, the formulation of Yao's principle involves the class of all probability distributions on inputs in ${\mathcal {X}}$ , denoted as ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Here, $\mathbb {E}$ is notation for the expected value, and $x\sim D$ means that x is a random variable distributed according to D .
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The left hand side of the formula gives the optimal performance that can be obtained by a deterministic algorithm A on a random input x (its average-case complexity), for a probability distribution D on inputs that is as hard as possible and with A being the algorithm that performs best against D .
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The right hand side gives the optimal performance that can be obtained by a random algorithm R on a deterministic input x (its expected complexity), when R has the best performance on its worst case inputs, and when x is a worst case input to R .
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The finiteness of ${\mathcal {A}}$ and ${\mathcal {X}}$ allows ${\mathcal {D}}$ and ${\mathcal {R}}$ to be interpreted as simplices of probability vectors, whose compactness implies that the minima and maxima in these formulas exist.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Another version of Yao's principle weakens it from an equality to an inequality, but at the same time generalizes it by relaxing the requirement that the algorithms and inputs come from a finite set.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The direction of the inequality allows it to be used when a specific input distribution has been shown to be hard for deterministic algorithms, converting it into a lower bound on the cost of all randomized algorithms.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] By avoiding maximization and minimization over ${\mathcal {D}}$ and ${\mathcal {R}}$ , this version of Yao's principle can apply in some cases where ${\mathcal {X}}$ or ${\mathcal {A}}$ are not finite.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Although this direction of inequality is the direction needed for proving lower bounds on randomized algorithms, the equality version of Yao's principle, when it is available, can also be useful in these proofs.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The equality of the principle implies that there is no loss of generality in using the principle to prove lower bounds: whatever the actual best randomized algorithm might be, there is some input distribution through which a matching lower bound on its complexity can be proven.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] When the cost c denotes the running time of an algorithm, Yao's principle states that the best possible running time of a deterministic algorithm, on a hard input distribution, gives a lower bound for the expected time of any Las Vegas algorithm on its worst-case input.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Here, a Las Vegas algorithm is a randomized algorithm whose runtime may vary, but for which the result is always correct.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] For example, this form of Yao's principle has been used to prove the optimality of certain Monte Carlo tree search algorithms for the exact evaluation of game trees.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The time complexity of comparison-based sorting and selection algorithms is often studied using the number of comparisons between pairs of data elements as a proxy for the total time.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] When these problems are considered over a fixed set of elements, their inputs can be expressed as permutations and a deterministic algorithm can be expressed as a decision tree.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In this way both the inputs and the algorithms form finite sets as Yao's principle requires.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] A symmetrization argument identifies the hardest input distributions: They are the random permutations, the distributions on n distinct elements for which all permutations are equally likely.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] This is because, if any other distribution were hardest, averaging it with all permutations of the same hard distribution would be equally hard, and would produce the distribution for a random permutation.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle extends lower bounds for the average case number of comparisons made by deterministic algorithms, for random permutations, to the worst case analysis of randomized comparison algorithms.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] An example given by Yao is the analysis of algorithms for finding the k th largest of a given set of n values, the selection problem.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Subsequently, to Yao's work, Walter Cunto and Ian Munro showed that, for random permutations, any deterministic algorithm must perform at least $n+\min(k,n-k)-O(1)$ expected comparisons.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] By Yao's principle, the same number of comparisons must be made by randomized algorithms on their worst-case input.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The Floyd–Rivest algorithm comes within $O({\sqrt {n\log n}})$ comparisons of this bound.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Another of the original applications by Yao of his principle was to the evasiveness of graph properties, the number of tests of the adjacency of pairs of vertices needed to determine whether a graph has a given property, when the only access to the graph is through such tests.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Karp conjectured that every randomized algorithm for every nontrivial monotone graph property (a property that remains true for every subgraph of a graph with the property) requires a quadratic number of tests, but only weaker bounds have been proven.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] As Yao stated, for graph properties that are true of the empty graph but false for some other graph on n vertices with only a bounded number s of edges, a randomized algorithm must probe a quadratic number of pairs of vertices.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] For instance, for the property of being a planar graph, $s=9$ because the 9-edge utility graph is non-planar.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] More precisely, Yao states that for these properties, at least $\left({\tfrac {1}{2}}-p\right){\tfrac {1}{s}}{\tbinom {n}{2}}$ tests are needed, for every $\varepsilon >0$ , for a randomized algorithm to have probability at most p of making a mistake.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao also used this method to show that quadratically many queries are needed for the properties of containing a given tree or clique as a subgraph, of containing a perfect matching, and of containing a Hamiltonian cycle, for small enough constant error probabilities.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In black-box optimization, the problem is to determine the minimum or maximum value of a function, from a given class of functions, accessible only through calls to the function on arguments from some finite domain.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In this case, the cost to be optimized is the number of calls.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle has been described as "the only method available for proving lower bounds for all randomized search heuristics for selected classes of problems".
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In communication complexity, an algorithm describes a communication protocol between two or more parties, and its cost may be the number of bits or messages transmitted between the parties.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In this case, Yao's principle describes an equality between the average-case complexity of deterministic communication protocols, on an input distribution that is the worst case for the problem, and the expected communication complexity of randomized protocols on their worst-case inputs.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] An example described by Avi Wigderson (based on a paper by Manu Viola) is the communication complexity for two parties, each holding n -bit input values, to determine which value is larger.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] For deterministic communication protocols, nothing better than n bits of communication is possible, easily achieved by one party sending their whole input to the other.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] However, parties with a shared source of randomness and a fixed error probability can exchange 1-bit hash functions of prefixes of the input to perform a noisy binary search for the first position where their inputs differ, achieving $O(\log n)$ bits of communication.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] This is within a constant factor of optimal, as can be shown via Yao's principle with an input distribution that chooses the position of the first difference uniformly at random, and then chooses random strings for the shared prefix up to that position and the rest of the inputs after that position.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle has also been applied to the competitive ratio of online algorithms.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] An online algorithm must respond to a sequence of requests, without knowledge of future requests, incurring some cost or profit per request depending on its choices.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The competitive ratio is the ratio of its cost or profit to the value that could be achieved by an *offline algorithm* with access to knowledge of all future requests, for a worst-case request sequence that causes this ratio to be as far from one as possible.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Here, one must be careful to formulate the ratio with the algorithm's performance in the numerator and the optimal performance of an offline algorithm in the denominator, so that the cost measure can be formulated as an expected value rather than as the reciprocal of an expected value.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] An example given by Borodin & El-Yaniv (2005) concerns page replacement algorithms, which respond to requests for pages of computer memory by using a cache of k pages, for a given parameter k .
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] If a request matches a cached page, it costs nothing; otherwise one of the cached pages must be replaced by the requested page, at a cost of one page fault.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] A difficult distribution of request sequences for this model can be generated by choosing each request uniformly at random from a pool of $k+1$ pages.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Any deterministic online algorithm has ${\tfrac {n}{k+1}}$ expected page faults, over n requests.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Instead, an offline algorithm can divide the request sequence into phases within which only k pages are used, incurring only one fault at the start of a phase to replace the one page that is unused within the phase.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] As an instance of the coupon collector's problem, the expected requests per phase is $(k+1)H_{k}$ , where $H_{k}=1+{\tfrac {1}{2}}+\cdots +{\tfrac {1}{k}}$ is the k th harmonic number.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] By renewal theory, the offline algorithm incurs ${\tfrac {n}{(k+1)H_{k}}}+o(n)$ page faults with high probability, so the competitive ratio of any deterministic algorithm against this input distribution is at least $H_{k}$ .
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] By Yao's principle, $H_{k}$ also lower bounds the competitive ratio of any randomized page replacement algorithm against a request sequence chosen by an *oblivious adversary* to be a worst case for the algorithm but without knowledge of the algorithm's random choices.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] For online problems in a general class related to the ski rental problem, Seiden has proposed a cookbook method for deriving optimally hard input distributions, based on certain parameters of the problem.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle may be interpreted in game theoretic terms, via a two-player zero-sum game in which one player, Alice, selects a deterministic algorithm, the other player, Bob, selects an input, and the payoff is the cost of the selected algorithm on the selected input.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Any randomized algorithm R may be interpreted as a randomized choice among deterministic algorithms, and thus as a mixed strategy for Alice.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Similarly, a non-random algorithm may be thought of as a pure strategy for Alice.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In any two-player zero-sum game, if one player chooses a mixed strategy, then the other player has an optimal pure strategy against it.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Thus, the minimax mixed strategy for Alice, set against the best opposing pure strategy for Bob, produces the same expected game value c as the minimax mixed strategy for Bob, set against the best opposing pure strategy for Alice.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] This equality of expected game values, for the game described above, is Yao's principle in its form as an equality.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Yao's 1977 paper, originally formulating Yao's principle, proved it in this way.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The optimal mixed strategy for Alice (a randomized algorithm) and the optimal mixed strategy for Bob (a hard input distribution) may each be computed using a linear program that has one player's probabilities as its variables, with a constraint on the game value for each choice of the other player.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The two linear programs obtained in this way for each player are dual linear programs, whose equality is an instance of linear programming duality.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] However, although linear programs may be solved in polynomial time, the numbers of variables and constraints in these linear programs (numbers of possible algorithms and inputs) are typically too large to list explicitly.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Therefore, formulating and solving these programs to find these optimal strategies is often impractical.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] For Monte Carlo algorithms, algorithms that use a fixed amount of computational resources but that may produce an erroneous result, a form of Yao's principle applies to the probability of an error, the error rate of an algorithm.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Choosing the hardest possible input distribution, and the algorithm that achieves the lowest error rate against that distribution, gives the same error rate as choosing an optimal algorithm and its worst case input distribution.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] However, the hard input distributions found in this way are not robust to changes in the parameters used when applying this principle.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] If an input distribution requires high complexity to achieve a certain error rate, it may nevertheless have unexpectedly low complexity for a different error rate.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Ben-David and Blais show that, for Boolean functions under many natural measures of computational complexity, there exists an input distribution that is simultaneously hard for all error rates.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] Variants of Yao's principle have also been considered for quantum computing.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] In place of randomized algorithms, one may consider quantum algorithms that have a good probability of computing the correct value for every input (probability at least ${\tfrac {2}{3}}$ ); this condition together with polynomial time defines the complexity class BQP.
[src:communication-complexity/yao-s-principle] The weak form of this inequality is within a constant factor of being an equality, but the strong form is not.
